"Berendes T., Sengupta S.K., Welch R.M., Wielicki B.A., Navar M.","Cumulus Cloud Base Height Estimation from High Spatial Resolution Landsat Data: A Hough Transform Approach",1992,"IEEE Transactions on Geoscience and Remote Sensing","30","3",,"430","443",,,10.1109/36.142921,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0026868264&partnerID=40&md5=fe903ea8324b04463e2fd3957c6b7976","Institute of Atmospheric Sciences (IAS), South Dakota School of Mines and Technology (SDSM&T), Rapid City, SD 57701-3995, United States; Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, University of California, Livermore, CA 94551, United States; Naval Oceanographic and Atmospheric Research Laboratory (NOARL), Monterey, CA 93943, United States; NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23665, United States","Berendes, T., Institute of Atmospheric Sciences (IAS), South Dakota School of Mines and Technology (SDSM&T), Rapid City, SD 57701-3995, United States; Sengupta, S.K., Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, University of California, Livermore, CA 94551, United States; Welch, R.M., Naval Oceanographic and Atmospheric Research Laboratory (NOARL), Monterey, CA 93943, United States; Wielicki, B.A., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23665, United States; Navar, M., Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, University of California, Livermore, CA 94551, United States","Cloud base height is an essential variable governing surface energy budgets, but it is notoriously difficult to determine using satellite data. This study develops a semiautomated methodology to estimate cumulus cloud base heights using high spatial resolution LANDSAT Multispectral Scanner data. The approach employs a variety of image processing techniques to match cloud edges with their corresponding shadow edges. Cloud base height then is estimated by computing the separation distance between the corresponding Generalized Hough Transform reference points. Sixteen subregions, each 30 km x 30 km in size, are selected for four LANDSAT scenes. Standard deviations of cloud base height within each of the subregions range from about 100m to 150m. Differences between cloud base heights computed using the Hough Transform and a manual verification technique are small (on the order of 100m or less). The cloud base heights also compare favorably with the few surface observations available. On the basis of these results, it is estimated that cloud base height accuracies of 50–70m may be possible using HIRIS and ASTER instruments in the EOS Global Climate Change program. © 1992 IEEE",,"Mathematical Transformations - Applications; Meteorology - Remote Sensing; Remote Sensing - Multispectral Scanners; Base Height Estimation; Cumulus Clouds; High Spatial Resolution Landsat Data; Hough Transform Approach; Meteorology",,,,,,"Stephens, G.L., Webster, P.J., Cloud decoupling of the surface and planetary radiative budgets (1984) J. Atmos. Sci., 41, pp. 681-686; Aida, M., Scattering of solar radiation as a function of cloud dimensions and orientation (1976) J. Quant. Spectrosc. Radiat. Transfer, 17, pp. 303-311; McKee, T.B., Cox, S.K., Simulated radiance patterns for finite cubic clouds (1976) J. Atmos. Sci., 33, pp. 2014-2020; Gupta, S.K., A parameterization for longwave surface radiation from satellite data (1989) J. Climate, 2, pp. 305-320; Radiation and climate. Report of the First Session (1988), (235). , JSC Working Group on Radiative Fluxes, WMO/TDFrouin, R., Gautier, C., Morcrette, J.J., Downward longwave irradiance at the ocean surface from satellite data: Methodology and in situ validation (1988) J. Geophys. Res., 93, pp. 597-619; Hasler, A.F., Stereographic observations from geosynchronous satellites: An important new tool for atmospheric sciences (1981) Bull. Amer. Meteorol. Soc., 62, pp. 194-212; Hambrick, L.N., Loew, M.H., Carroll, R.L., Jr., The entry-exit method of shadow boundary segmentation (1987) IEEE Trans. Pattern. Anal. Machine Intell., PAMI-9, pp. 597-607; Gurney, C.M., The use of 